    "score" : 30,
    "last_activity_date" : 1275220509,
    "creation_date" : 1275220509,
    "answer_id" : 2938490,
    "question_id" : 2938476,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 2.5",
    "body" : "<p>The first two are equivalent, but the \"null != object\" is an old practice from languages where it is valid to write \"if (object = null)\" and accidentally assign null to the object. It is a guard to stop this accident from happening.</p>\n\n<p>The second whilst equivalent has the added advantage that if \"something\" is null you will not get a null reference exception whereas you would if you did: something\".equals(\"\").</p>\n"
  } ],
